Sometimes I feel very ashamed to be a European
Over a million people arrived in Europe last year needing our help and our response was frankly pathetic
There are so many contradictions here
We mourn the tragic death of two-year-old Alan Cody, but since then more than two hundred children have drowned in the Mediterranean.
We have international conventions that recognize that hosting refugees is a shared responsibility among all countries, yet we accept that tiny Lebanon takes in more Syrians than the whole of Europe.
We decry the existence of human smuggling yet we make it the only viable way to seek asylum in Europe
We have a labor shortage and yet we prevent those who could meet our economic and demographic needs from entering Europe
We claim that our liberal values are contrary to those espoused by Islamic fundamentalists. Yet - we use repressive policies to detain child asylum seekers, separate children from their families, and forcibly confiscate refugee property.
What are we doing
How did the situation get to this point? We are responding to a humanitarian crisis in an inhumane way.
I don&#39;t believe it because people don&#39;t care. At least I don&#39;t want to believe it.
I think this is due to a lack of foresight on the part of our politicians to adapt to a changing and globalized world that was proposed fifty years ago.
The International Refugee System So what I want to do is take a step back and ask two very basic questions that we all have to understand.
First of all why the existing system doesn’t work
Secondly, how do we solve
The modern refugee system was developed after World War II by these people
Its original intention was to ensure that when a country collapsed, or worse, a regime became hostile to its people, those people had a place to go and live there in safety and dignity until they could return home.
This is exactly what we are seeing in Syria today
Through the 1951 Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees, an international conference signed by 147 governments, and an international organization, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), commitments are made to member states to allow entry into their territories for people fleeing conflict, conflict and persecution.
But now the system is collapsing
Refugees have the theoretical right to seek asylum
The reality is that our immigration policies block this path to safety
Refugees theoretically have the right to seek equal treatment or the option to return to their home country
But in practice they are stuck in an almost indefinite state of stagnation.
Theoretically, the refugee problem is the responsibility of all countries.
In practice, geographical location means that countries close to conflict are overloaded with receiving the vast majority of refugees.
The rules of the original refugee system were not the cause of its collapse
It&#39;s that we haven&#39;t used it enough as the world changes. That&#39;s what we need to reconsider.
So I want to explain to you how the system works today
How does the current refugee admission system work?
But this is not from a top-down macro perspective but from the perspective of individual refugees.
So imagine a Syrian woman
Let&#39;s call her Amira
Amira represents the many refugees I meet in the region
Amira, like about a quarter of the world&#39;s refugees, is a woman with a child. She cannot return home because her city, which you see now in Homs, once a beautiful and historic city, is now devastated.
So Amira can&#39;t go back
Amira also has no hope of resettling in a third country because that would be like winning the lottery, something only less than one percent of refugees in the world can win.
So Amira and her family face an almost impossible choice
They have three basic options
The first one is that Amira can take her family to the refugee camp
She might get help in the refugee camp but the prospects for Amira and her family are very slim.
The camp is located in a desolate and barren area, usually a desert
At the Za&#39;atalina camp in Jordan you can hear the sound of shells coming across the Syrian border at night
Economic activity there is restricted
The quality of education is often low
And about 80% of refugees in refugee camps around the world have to stay there for at least five years.
This is where the tragedy lies, which may also explain why in reality only nine percent of Syrians choose this option
Or Amira can travel to a city area in a neighboring city such as Amman or Beirut
Seventy-five percent of Syrian refugees choose this option
But even there it was difficult
Refugees in cities often do not have the right to work
They often have no access to assistance
So when Amira and her family used up their basic savings, they had little left and were likely to face poverty.
There is a third option being chosen by an increasing number of Syrians
Amira can seek hope for her family by embarking on a dangerous journey to another country that could cost her life. This is what we see in Europe today.
Globally we are left with an almost impossible choice for refugees. Among these three options are refugee camps, cities, poverty and dangerous journeys.
For refugees this option is today’s global refugee regime
But I think this is a wrong choice
I think we can revisit this option
The reason we limit these options is because we think these are the only options available to refugees but they are not
Politicians have framed it as a matter of gains and losses. If refugees gain, citizens have to bear the loss.
We seem to agree with the assumption that refugees are an inevitable burden and cost to society
But this is not a stereotype refugees can contribute
So what I want to demonstrate is that we have ways to increase that option and still benefit everyone: including host countries and communities, our society, and the refugees themselves
I would like to propose four ways to transform our established thinking about refugees
What these four approaches have in common is that we have taken advantage of the opportunities of globalization, social mobility and markets to update our understanding of refugee issues.
The first thing I want to consider is the concept of creating environments. This comes from a very basic understanding that refugees are just like all other people; they are just in a certain environment.
My colleagues at the University of Oxford and I have begun a research project in Uganda examining the economic lives of refugees
We did not choose Uganda because it is a typical example of a receiving country
it is exactly an exception
Unlike most host countries around the world, what Uganda does is give refugees economic opportunities.
Give them the right to work and give them freedom of movement
The consequences are staggering, both for refugees and for host countries.
In Kampala, the capital of Uganda, we found that 21 percent of refugees opened their own businesses and employed others, and 40 percent of those employed were nationals of the host country.
In other words, refugees are creating jobs for citizens of the host country.
Even in refugee camps we found examples of dynamic, thriving entrepreneurial businesses
For example, in a refugee camp called Nakiwale we found Congolese refugees running a business trading digital music.
We found a Rwandan refugee business that allows young people to play computer games on recycled consoles and monitors
Refugees are constantly innovating despite extreme constraints. The person in front of you is a Congolese named Damon Kay.
He arrived at the refugee camp with little money but wanted to be a filmmaker
So with friends and colleagues he started a community radio station, he rented a video camera and he&#39;s now making movies
He has filmed two documentaries with and for our team and has built a successful career from very few resources.
It is precisely this kind of example that should dominate our response to refugees
Rather than assuming that refugees are inevitably dependent on humanitarian aid we need to provide them with opportunities to flourish as human beings
Yes, clothing, blankets, shelter, and food are all very important during the emergency phase, but we must also think long-term.
We need to provide connectivity, access to electricity, education, access to jobs, funding and business
All the access to the global economy that we take for granted can and should be made available to refugees
The second idea I want to discuss is economic zones
Unfortunately not all host countries in the world have adopted Uganda’s policies
Most host economies are closed to refugees but we still have viable alternatives
Last April I traveled to Jordan with my colleague, development economist Paul Corea, where we discussed an idea with the international community and the local government to bring jobs to Syrians while advancing Jordan&#39;s national development strategy.
The idea is to create an economic zone in which we can combine employment of refugees with employment of nationals of the host country Jordan
Just a 15-minute drive outside the Zaatari refugee camp, which houses 83,000 refugees, is an active economic zone known as the King Hussein Development Zone.
The government has invested more than $100 million to connect power grids and roads but it still lacks two things: labor and foreign investment.
So what if instead of being stuck in a refugee camp, refugees could work there and be able to support their families and develop their skills through vocational training before returning to Syria?
We recognize that doing so benefits Jordan as its national development strategy calls for upgrading manufacturing as a middle-income country
Doing so benefits refugees while also aiding Syria&#39;s post-war reconstruction by recognizing that we need to nurture refugees as the best resource for ultimately rebuilding Syria
We published this view in the journal Foreign Affairs
King Abdullah of Jordan also adopted the idea
It was announced two weeks ago at the London Syria Conference that the pilot project would begin this summer.
