We rarely ask refugees what they want or where they want to go but I argue that it can be done while benefiting everyone
Economist Alvin Ross created the concept of a matching market, in which the order of preferences of both parties determines the final match.
My colleagues Will Jones and Eric Stateboy looked at how to apply this concept to the refugee problem. They asked refugees to rank their preferred countries but also allowed countries to rank the types of refugees they wanted to accept based on skills or language. The standard finally matches the two sortings
Of course you need to establish quotas in terms of diversity and vulnerability but this is a way to increase the likelihood of pairing
This matching concept has been used successfully, for example, to match students and universities to match kidney donors and patients. It also highlights the importance of algorithms in dating sites.
So why not apply it to give refugees better options?
The same applies to the national level where the biggest problem we face is convincing local communities to accept refugees.
Taking my country as an example, we often send engineers to remote areas and farmers to cities. It makes no sense at all.
So matching markets offer a potential way to match these preferences and reflect the needs and requirements of the people in the receiving countries as well as the refugees
My fourth idea is a humanitarian visa
Much of the tragedy and chaos we see in Europe is completely avoidable
This stems from a fundamental contradiction in European asylum policy: in order to seek asylum in Europe you have to make it to Europe on your own, taking a dangerous journey that I described earlier. But why are these journeys necessary?
In an era of low-cost airlines and consulates?
These were completely unnecessary journeys that led to the deaths of more than three thousand people at European borders and within Europe last year
We could avoid these deaths if refugees were able to travel directly to Europe and seek asylum. This is indeed possible through humanitarian visas, which allow people to pick up a visa at an embassy or consulate in a neighboring country and then pay their own way to Europe by cruise ship or plane.
It costs about a thousand euros to bring a stowaway from Turkey to the Greek Islands
It only costs 200 euros to fly from Bodrum, Turkey to Frankfurt, Germany with a low-cost airline
If we allow them to do this it will be extremely fruitful
This would save lives, eradicate the market for illegal immigrants and eliminate the chaos we see on the fringes of Europe in areas like the Greek Islands.
What&#39;s stopping us from implementing this is politics rather than rational solutions
and this is an idea that has been applied
Brazil was the first to adopt this policy. More than 2,000 Syrians were granted humanitarian visas to enter Brazil and were granted refugee status upon entry.
In that program every Syrian was granted refugee status and confirmed to be a genuine refugee
There is also a historical precedent
Between 1922 and 1942 these Nansen passports served as entry and exit documents allowing 450,000 Assyrians, Turks and Chechens to cross Europe and apply for refugee status elsewhere in Europe
