We sailed east from the African coastline, across the vast Indian Ocean, and arrived at the Maldives, an archipelago composed of coral reefs.
During the stormy southwest monsoon season, manta rays living in the archipelago waters will gather near a small island called Hanifaru in Baa Atoll.
Groups of small shrimps and crabs, most of which are smaller than our pupils, are the main food of manta rays.
When these plankton are dispersed, manta rays usually feed alone, rolling backwards in the water like puppies chasing their tails.
When more and more plankton gather, the manta rays begin to line up end to end, forming a long feeding formation. The delicious food missed by the manta ray at the head of the team will be swallowed up by the companions behind it.
As more and more plankton gather in the bay, the formations of manta rays also get closer and closer. This unique feeding method is what we call the &quot;whirlwind feeding method.&quot;
The manta rays are stacked on top of each other, rotating in a tight formation, forming a vortex, sucking in plankton, and sending them straight into the manta ray&#39;s huge mouth.
Diving among hundreds of manta rays is a sight I will never forget.
When I first went to take pictures in Hanifaru, the area had not yet been protected and the ecological environment was threatened by local development.
Working with NGOs such as the Manta Trust, my photos helped Hanifaru become a marine reserve.
Fishermen from nearby islands once killed many manta rays and used their skins to make traditional drums.
Today, they have become the staunchest protectors of the manta rays, which bring more than $8 million in revenue to the Maldives every year.
