When I moved to Harare in 1985 social justice issues were at the heart of Zimbabwe&#39;s national health policy
The new government immediately announced a socialist policy after emerging from the long war of independence: making health care services and primary education basically free projects
Large-scale rural health services are within two hours&#39; walk of 80% of the population. This is truly extraordinary progress.
In 1980, the year of Zimbabwe’s independence, 25% of children were routinely immunized
By 1990, just ten years later this proportion had risen to 80%
I am honored to be a part of this transformation, this revolution
The excitement and camaraderie are very real.
Working side by side with the remarkable people, scientists, doctors, and activists of Zimbabwe, I felt part of not just an African independence movement but a progressive global public health movement.
I&#39;ve also faced some daunting difficulties
In 1985, the year I arrived, the first case of AIDS was reported in Zimbabwe.
I cared for several AIDS patients in the early 1980s while I was doing my medical training at Harlem Hospital, but... we had no idea what we were going to encounter in Africa.
When I first got there, the infection rate was about 2%
This ratio increased rapidly. By the time I left Harare 17 years later, one in four adults was infected.
